dha and the Medieval West: Changing Perspectives on Cultural Exchange between Asia and Europe in the Middle Ages / rSchmitz-Esser, Romedio -- tAt Home and on the Road: Comparing Food Cultures in the Medieval Low Countries / rStabel, Peter / Baatsen, Inneke -- tThe Revealing Peregrinations of Margery Kempe / rRoss, Lia -- tSpatial Configurations, Movement, and Identity in Chaucer's Romances / rScott, Anne -- t"Make a Pilgrimage for Me": The Role of Place in Late Medieval Proxy Pilgrimage / rFort, Gavin -- tTime and Space in Late-Medieval Dynastic Chronicles: With a Focus on Examples from Czech-Language Literature / rKoten, Jiří -- tMiracles, Marvels, and the Plague in the Czech-Written Travelogue by Christopher Harant of Polžice and Bezdružice (1564-1621) / rTomíček, David -- tTraveling Carpenters: The Russell Family of Westminster in the Early Sixteenth Century / rStanford, Charlotte A. -- tTravels with Johann Reuchlin: Linguist, Lawyer, and Christian Cabalist / rWillard, Thomas -- tPersonality Type and Prison Survival in Early Modern Spain. The Spiritual Move from Inside to the Outside: The Inquisitorial Trials of Fray Luis de León, Gaspar de Grajal, Martín Martínez Cantalapiedra, and Alonso Gudiel / rFulton, J. Michael -- tMobility, Space and the Pícara's Identity in Alonso de Salas Barbadillo's La hija de Celestina / rMorillo, María Dolores -- tThe Journey within the Journey: Catabasis and Travel Narrative in Late Medieval and Early Modern Epic / rTormey, Warren -- tVoyage to India with Sir William Jones: The Asiatick Society Remakes the West. The Travel of Texts and Their Transformative Power on Culture / rFrench, Aaron -- tSpace, Time, and Identity: Giovanni Battista Piranesi and the Epidemic of Ennui in the Pre-Modern West / rCoudert, Allison P. -- tIndex  aResearch on medieval and early modern travel literature has made great progress, which now allows us to take the next step and to analyze the correlations between the individual and space throughout time, which contributed essentially to identity formation in many different settings. The contributors to this volume engage with a variety of pre-modern texts, images, and other documents related to travel and the individual's self-orientation in foreign lands and make an effort to determine the concept of identity within a spatial framework often determined by the meeting of various cultures. Moreover, objects, images and words can also travel and connect people from different worlds through books. The volume thus brings together new scholarship focused on the interrelationship of travel, space, time, and individuality, which also includes, of course, women's movement through the larger world, whether in concrete terms or through proxy travel via readings. Travel here is also examined with respect to craftsmen's activities at various sites, artists' employment for many different projects all over Europe and elsewhere, and in terms of metaphysical experiences (catabasis).   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Nov 2018)1 aClassen, Albrecht, eeditor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2018 Englishz978311060403008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2018z9783110603149oZDB-23-DEG0 cEPUBz97831106097070 cprintz978311059503140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783110610963423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783110610963.jpg  a978-3-11-060403-0  EBOOK PACKAGE History 2018 Englishb2018  a978-3-11-060425-2  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishb2018  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_